{"key":"processedPost-11963708","value":{"id":11963708,"first":11962363,"last":12455973,"when":1265332995,"utime":"02/05/10 03:23 AM","content":"Wetspot is not caused by being too wet.&nbsp; If so, every LC would have it.&nbsp; Wetspot is a generic term for bacterial contamination, the most common cause of which is the breath or dirty fingernails of the cultivator himself.<br /><br />Don't soak over 24 hours, and definitely don't burst your kernels.&nbsp; WBS is not cheap when you can get organic rye berries for $20 per 50 pound bag from azurestandard.com.&nbsp; If you're getting bacteria, it means you're not being sterile in your post-sterilization procedures, and/or your filtering method is not adequate.<br /><br />Don't work in front of a hepa filter if it's one of those made in china plastic units from department or home improvement stores.&nbsp; Use a glovebox and shut off all heat or air conditioning, fans, hepa filters, etc.&nbsp; If you can afford a laminar flow hood, get one.&nbsp; I suspect you're not following good sterile technique though.<br />RR","title":"Re: Wetspot is insidious!","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}